[2] Summaries
- Thu 19 Sep 2019. Ebola uptick amid DRC security incidents
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) News Scan, abridged, edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/09/news-scan-sep-19-2019

Ebola transmission intensity increased slightly in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) outbreak region last week [11-17 Sep 2019], with 57 new confirmed cases amid minor security flare-ups and major violence in Mandima health zone that suspended response operations, the World Health Organization (WHO) said today [19 Sep 2019] in its weekly snapshot of the outbreak.

The major incident, 1st reported yesterday [18 Sep 2019], was community violence in Lwemba in Mandima health zone that was sparked by the death of a local health worker from Ebola. The WHO said the event has serious impact on response activities and could lead to gaps or delays in reporting in the area, which is one of the Ebola hot spots. The minor incidents affected safe and dignified burials and vaccination in Mambasa and Komanda health zones.

The WHO said most cases over the past 3 weeks are from 3 hot spots: Kalunguta, Mambasa, and Mandima. It added that cases in Beni have declined.

In other developments, 5 new cases were reported in the DRC, raising the outbreak total to 3150, according to numbers reflected on the WHO's online Ebola dashboard. Health officials are still investigating 430 suspected cases, and the death toll is at 2103, reflecting 5 more fatalities.

The DRC's multisector Ebola response committee (CMRE) provided a few more details on the 15 cases reported yesterday [18 Sep 2019]. The patients are from Mambasa (5), Beni (4), Kalunguta (4), Komanda (1), and Mandima (1). Of 5 new deaths noted in the CMRE report, 2 occurred in community settings, which raises the risk of further spread.

