[3] Response
- Thu 19 Sep 2019. Violence: Mandima health zone
[Daily Mail, abridged, edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-7483567/Violence-hinders-DR-Congo-Ebola-response-amid-hike-cases-WHO.html

The World Health Organization warned Thursday [19 Sep 2019] that violence in northeastern Democratic Republic of Congo had halted efforts to rein in Ebola in one area, even as the spread of the deadly virus intensified.

The UN health agency ... warned that transmission appeared to be worsening, after DRC's hard-hit North Kivu and Ituri provinces registered 57 new confirmed Ebola cases in the week leading up to [17 Sep 2019], compared with 40 new cases a week earlier.

At the same time, WHO said, a number of "localised, minor security incidents" continue to mar the response to the outbreak, including impeding safe burials of the highly contagious bodies and the administering of vaccines around Mambasa and Komanda.

Even more concerning was a 4-day "major security incident" that erupted in Lwemba, in the Mandima health zone in the northeastern Ituri province, last Friday [13 Sep 2019] in reaction to the Ebola death of a local healthcare worker.

"Due to the violence that occurred during the incident, all activities have been suspended in the area until further notice," WHO said. The UN health agency, which has declared the epidemic a "public health emergency of international concern", said the suspension was having "a serious impact on the response activities on the ground".

"It could lead to gaps or delays in the reporting of new (Ebola) cases in this hotspot area," it cautioned. Such incidents, it said, highlighted the vital need for continued and proactive engagement with communities in impacted areas.

